[Meningitis is caused predominantly by microorganisms (bacteria,
viruses, parasites, and fungi). These microorganisms infect the blood
and the cerebrospinal fluid. Viral meningitis is generally less
severe and resolves without specific treatment. Viral meningitis
(also called aseptic meningitis) is an infection that causes
inflammation of the layers (meninges) that surround the brain and
spinal cord. Many different viruses can cause meningitis; the most
common are the enteroviruses. These viruses are present in the
intestines and can cause colds, sore throats, stomach upsets and
diarrhoea. Only rarely do these viruses spread through the body to
the meninges causing meningitis.

Enteroviruses are most often spread from person to person through
fecal contamination, and through respiratory secretions (saliva,
sputum, or nasal mucus) of an infected person. When an enterovirus
causing meningitis is identified, it is usually either a
coxsackievirus or an echovirus.

Individuals and parties visiting countries with less well-developed
economies and variable standards of personal and community hygiene
are likely to expose themselves to common enteric viruses to which
they have little preexisting immunity. This is evident in the party
of children from Canada visiting the Dominical Republic and spreading
infection in their home country on their return. Fortunately
enteroviral meningitis is a mild condition generally without serious outcomes.

ProMED-mail is indebted to Professor David Patrick for providing this
detailed account of the analysis of this outbreak. It would be useful
to know the precise identity (species of enterovirus) responsible for
this outbreak, if this information becomes available in due course.

The HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Canada is available at
<http://healthmap.org/r/007x >, and that of the Dominican Republic at
<http://healthmap.org/r/ 00NY>. - Mod.CP]
